        'Treating all growth as a permanent acceleration: Most policy changes (higher saving rates, one-time capital investment) produce level effects — a new, higher GDP plateau — not a permanently faster growth rate. Only sustained TFP improvements create lasting growth-rate effects.',
        'Assuming a strong GDP growth rate means high living standards: GDP per capita growth is the correct welfare measure; fast aggregate GDP growth in a country with rapid population expansion may leave individuals no better off.',
